That said, I make it a point not to insult other people's religions.  I do however make it a point to insult people's politics, Democrats and Republicans especially.  Again, that's another rant. :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> One major difference between my faith and the Christian one is the idea of forgiveness and redemption. The Christian faith preaches that it is not good works that will get you into Heaven, but instead being &quot;born again&quot; in Christ and accepting him as your saviour. Asking him forgiveness for your sins.  My faith doesn't teach that. We don't believe that being forgiven is enough. You must work to erase the deed. Your life is measured through the good you have done.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually there are also Christian faiths, most notably the Catholic church, that believe that salvation is gained through both faith AND works.  There must be belief in the Lord, belief that he is the savior, but there also must be evidence of that belief in how you live your life.  I think pretty much a majority of protestant denominations take the Sola Fides (&quot;faith alone&quot;) interpretation -- it was one of Luther's and Protestantism's greatest disagreements with Catholics.<br>
<br>
Even after I stopped practicing Catholicism, and became more and more agnostic, I still pretty much look at scripture and Christianity from a Catholic viewpoint... and to this day I've always thought that the 'utter a salvation prayer and you're saved, all your sins are magically erased!' was an incorrect interpretation, and an incredible denial of many parts of scripture and Tradition.  However, neither then, nor now, do I think this disagreement makes Protestants any less Christian than Catholics.  I think there is a genuine, honest disagreement there in interpretation that will probably never be reconciled.  <br>
<br>
So again, you are attempting to generalize all christians as the same here.  You use the term &quot;Christians&quot; and &quot;Christianity&quot; as if it is the same throughout; here's proof that its not, you've generalized here about an EXTREMELY important issue among Christians (the sola fides issue) and made a completely inaccurate and generalized statement about it.  Haven't you figured out, after this entire thread, that there are so many different types of Christianity that you just can't do that?<br>
<br>
