<br>
To whoever wanted to put me down for attending different denominations while still young, calling me a religion shopper or something to that effect:<br>
<br>
I should be ashamed for trying to educate myself? For learning, from the source, different denominational beliefs concerning how to live your life and what comprises a Christian life? I don't think so. Cast aspersions on my character all you like, when I have curiousity about a subject, I educate myself on the matter as much as possible. Then I make up my mind what I think or believe. I don't spend my time half-heartedly. Time is precious, I spend it doing what I enjoy.<br>
<br>
I don't deny anyone else their opinion, neither do I refrain from expressing mine. If that expression sometimes descends to sarcasm, que sera sera. U tend to address certain people in terms they can understand. If it upsets them, that's their problem and not mine. I can't see getting upset about a discussion centering on a subject that has indeed been beaten like a dead horse. Great minds have debated many of the aspects of this discussion throughout the past. As Lanaya stated, the discussion concerning adherence to the Old Testament laws began immediately after the death of Christ. Christ addressed it prior to his death. He basically informed the disciples that salvation was for all mankind, not just the Hebrews. If I remember correctly (all my books are packed still) this discussion was pretty much summed by Christ:<br>
<br>
&quot;...In my father's house are many mansions...&quot;<br>
<br>
If memory serves me, this was part of the culmination of the lesson where Christ basically told the disciples to worry about their own salvation and let everyone else worry about theirs. Not that you couldn't &quot;testify&quot; to others, or minister to others, but that it wasn't the place of the Christian to decide who the Holy Trinity would allow into Heaven; that is, who might be saved. This decision is reserved for the deity. With the exception of denying Christ, he states that no one is beyond salvation.<br>
<br>
This is the origin of the debate about faith and works. If you repent and accept Christ on your death bed, after a life of sin, are you saved? According to the teachings of Christ, yes. According to some denominations, no. <br>
<br>
What was it Christ said about straining at a gnat?<br>
